@CAPS1 hour and thirty minutes, are you kidding! That’s what I thought when I first saw the line outside the amusement park. My friends and I had been so excited to come here, but now I began to wonder if it was worth the wait. As we slowly made our way forward, I noticed some other people in the line were getting impatient. A couple of girls were complaining about how hot it was, and one boy was loudly announcing that he wouldn’t wait this long for anything. But as the hours passed by, I started to realize that I was actually okay with waiting. 

Being patient means that you are understanding and tolerant. A patient person experiences difficulties without complaining. As the line moved forward inch by inch, I looked around and saw that there were people from all walks of life who had come here to have a good time, just like me. We were all waiting for the same thing, and that made me feel a sense of unity that I hadn’t expected. As I talked to some of the other people in line, I learned about their lives, their dreams, and their struggles. Listening to them made me forget about the discomfort of waiting and made me appreciate the fact that I was able to be in this moment, right now, with these amazing people. 

Even as the sun went down and the line started moving faster, I found myself hoping that it wouldn’t end too soon. I had learned something valuable about myself and about others: that sometimes, the journey is just as important as the destination. As we finally reached the front of the line and stepped onto the rollercoaster, I couldn’t help but feel grateful for the experience that had led up to this moment. And as we rode the wild twists and turns, I knew that the wait had been worth it. Because in the end, patience had brought me something I would never forget.
